Of course, I claim that the coincidence of Selimus and Tamhurlaine borrowing identical material from the same poem of Spenser is an argument in favour ofi the Marlowe authorship of both plays. But I deny that the same argument can hold good in respect to Locrine, which copies Selimus almost as outra- geously as it does Spenser. The author of Locrine merely happened to discover that Selimus had obtained a small portion of its material from The Ruines of Rome, and he followed suit, but with less discretion and infinitely less ability.
